ctionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Pedro, Alicia, Fernando, Manuel, Rafael, Adolfo, Alfredo, Ana, Areli, Candita.  French Adrien, Andre, Eugenie, Francoise.","English; Spanish (<b>Crispín</b>): from the personal name Middle English <i>Crispin</i>, Spanish <i>Crispín</i>, from Latin <i>Crispinus</i>, derived from <i>crispus</i> ‘curly-haired’ (see   Crisp  ). This name was especially popular in France in the early Middle Ages, having been borne by a Christian saint who was martyred at Soissons in  AD <i>c.</i> 285 along with a companion, <i>Crispinianus</i> (whose name is a further derivative of the same word). Compare   Crespin   and 3 below.","English (of Norman origin): from Old French and Middle English <i>crespin</i>, <i>crispin</i> ‘curly-haired’, also found as <i>Crepin</i>; see   Crippin  . It is difficult to tell this apart from the personal name in 1 above. According to Lanfranc, archbishop of Canterbury (1070–1089), the Norman Gilbert Crispin was the first man to receive this nickname, and two of his sons adopted it as their surname. His grandson Gilbert Crispin became abbot of Westminster in 1085. Members of the Norman family were said to have inherited a shock of hair that stood up stiffly like a bristly pine, as though the name derived from Latin <i>crispus pinus</i>, but this derivation is a medieval invention."],"variants":[{"name":"Crisp","meanings":["English: nickname for a man with curly hair, from Middle English <i>crisp</i>, <i>crips</i>, <i>scrip</i>, Old English <i>crisp</i>, <i>cryps</i> (from Latin <i>crispus</i>), reinforced in Middle English by an Old French word also from Latin <i>crispus</i>. In some cases this is possibly a nickname from the personal name   Crispin  .","Americanized form of German <b>Krisp</b>: nickname from Middle High German <i>krisp</i>, <i>krispel</i> ‘curly-haired man’.","Americanized form of German <b>Krisp</b>: from a short form of the medieval personal name <i>Krispin</i> (see   Crispin  )."]},{"name":"Crippen","meanings":["English: variant of   Crispin  .","Irish: variant of   Gribbin  ."]},{"name":"Crespin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Carlos, Raul, Vidal, Adelina, Alfonso, Amador, Andres, Aniceto, Delfino, Emilio.","Spanish (<b>Crespín</b>): variant of   Crispin  .","French: from the Latin personal name <i>Crispinus</i> (see   Crispin  )."]},{"name":"Crispen","meanings":["English: variant of   Crispin  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain.","Americanized form of German <b>Krispin</b>, a cognate of   Crispin  ."]},{"name":"Crispino","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Luigi, Carlo, Amato, Angelo, Antonio, Domenico, Fiore, Gennaro, Michelina, Rocco, Sal, Salvator.","Italian (southern): from the personal name <i>Crispino</i>, from Latin <i>Crispinus</i>, a derivative of the old Roman surname <i>Crispus</i> ‘curly(-headed)’ (see   Crispin  )."]},{"name":"Crippin","meanings":["English: variant of   Crispin  .","Irish: variant of   Gribbin  ."]},{"name":"Crespi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jaime, Juan, Mercedes, Racquel, Alberto, Alejandro, Consuelo, Eduardo, Jose, Jose Manuel, Migdalia, Pedro.  Jewish Aron, Nissim.","Catalan (<b>Crespí</b>): from a personal name, the Catalan equivalent of   Crispin  .","Italian (northern): variant of   Crespo  ."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Gilbert Crispin Lord of Tillières was born about 1100, in Normandy, France. He had at least 1 son with Juliana Aigle. He died before 1190, in Eure, Normandy, France."},"et":{"Abt 1100–Bef 1190":"umbes 1100–enne 1190","1108–1156":"1108–1156","1120–1190":"1120–1190","1100–1190":"1100–1190","1190":"1190","Abt 1100":"umbes 1100","1156":"1156","1100":"1100","1120":"1120","Bef 1190":"enne 1190","1108":"1108","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Tilly-sur-Seulles, Calvador, France":"Tilly-sur-Seulles, Calvados, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Eure, Normandy, France":"Eure, Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Anjou, France":"Anjou, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1100–Bef 1190":"noin 1100–ennen vuotta 1190","1108–1156":"1108–1156","1120–1190":"1120–1190","1100–1190":"1100–1190","1190":"1190","Abt 1100":"noin 1100","1156":"1156","1100":"1100","1120":"1120","Bef 1190":"ennen vuotta 1190","1108":"1108","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Ranska","Tilly-sur-Seulles, Calvador, France":"Tilly-sur-Seulles, Calvados, Normandie, Ranska","Eure, Normandy, France":"Eure, Normandie, Ranska","Anjou, France":"Anjou, Ranska"},"fr":{"Abt 1100–Bef 1190":"environ 1100–avant 1190","1108–1156":"1108–1156","1120–1190":"1120–1190","1100–1190":"1100–1190","1190":"1190","Abt 1100":"environ 1100","1156":"1156","1100":"1100","1120":"1120","Bef 1190":"avant 1190","1108":"1108","Normandie, France":"Normandie, France","Tilly-sur-Seulles, Calvador, France":"Tilly-sur-Seulles, Calvados, Normandie, France","Eure, Normandy, France":"Eure, Normandie, France","Anjou, France":"Anjou, France","lifeSummary":"Gilbert Crispin Lord of Tillières est né environ 1100, à Normandie, France. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Juliana Aigle. Il est décédé avant 1190, à Eure, Normandie, France."},"de":{"Abt 1100–Bef 1190":"um 1100–vor 1190","1108–1156":"1108–1156","1120–1190":"1120–1190","1100–1190":"1100–1190","1190":"1190","Abt 1100":"um 1100","1156"